  "local_port": 44782,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm 4 years into my H1B, my GC is not yet started. If I apply GC through consulting company, do I need to join this company before filing I-140/I485?",
  "response": "In the context of employment-based green card (GC) applications in the United States, the process typically involves several stages, including the PERM Labor Certification, I-140 Immigrant Petition, and potentially the I-485 Adjustment of Status if you're adjusting status within the U.S.\n\n1. **PERM Labor Certification**: This is the first step in most employment-based green card processes and involves the employer demonstrating that there are no qualified U.S. workers available for the position.\n\n2. **I-140 Immigrant Petition**: Once the PERM is approved, the employer can file an I-140 on your behalf. This petition establishes your eligibility for an immigrant visa based on your employment.\n\n3. **I-485 Adjustment of Status**: If you are in the U.S. and your priority date is current, you can file an I-485 to adjust your status to that of a permanent resident.\n\nRegarding your specific question about joining the consulting company before filing the I-140 or I-485:\n\n- Generally, for an I-140 to be filed, there is no requirement for you to be employed by the company at the time of filing. The I-140 petition is based on a future job offer. This means the consulting company can file an I-140 on your behalf as a prospective employer.\n\n- However, for the I-485, typically, the applicant is expected to intend to work for the sponsoring employer upon receiving the green card, and the employer intends to employ the applicant. While actual employment is not strictly required at the I-485 stage, it is essential that both parties intend to enter into an employment relationship.\n\nBefore making any decisions, it would be advisable to consult with an immigration attorney to discuss your specific situation and ensure you're meeting all necessary legal requirements. Immigration law can be complex, and an attorney can provide you with guidance tailored to your circumstances.",
